(fifthQuint)Remote Ischemic Preconditioning Combined to Local Ischemic Postconditioning in Acute Myocardial Infarction.

 In the management of STEMI, prompt reperfusion of the jeopardized myocardium is the most effective way to limit infarct size, which is a major determinant of morbidity and mortality.

 However, restoration of blood flow may paradoxically have deleterious consequences and lead to lethal myocardial ischemia-reperfusion injury.

 Local ischemic postconditioning (IPost) and remote ischemic preconditioning (RIPer) are promising methods to decrease ischemia-reperfusion injury.

 The hypothesis tested in this research proposal is that RIPer initiated at the time of the admission in the cathlab reduces infarct size in STEMI patients treated with PCI.

 Furthermore, the investigators will determine whether a combined approach RIPer + IPost can further reduce infarct size.

